pr_body:
Lists and tuples will be converted into dicts using enumerate().
This means that a dict such as:
d = {'list': ['a', 'b', 'c',]}
Will be flattened as follows:
flat = {'list:0': 'a', 'list:1': 'b', 'list:2': 'c'}
I also made some indentation changes for consistency.

This adds a --ipv6 option to tcset, so you can run `tcset  --device eth1 --delay 5 --ipv6 --overwrite --network ::2/128`.

Limitations:

* you need to provide a network to tcset, otherwise it defaults to 0.0.0.0/0 which is unhelpful
* tcshow recognises IPv6, but doesn't parse out the destination network:

```
$ tcshow --device eth1
{
    "eth1": {
        "outgoing": {
            "protocol=ipv6": {
                "delay": "5.0",
                "rate": "32000M"
            }
        },
        "incoming": {}
    }
}
```

This is because the output of `tc filter`, for quantities more than 32 bits, is much harder to parse and reconstruct:

```
tc filter show dev eth1
filter parent 16f1: protocol ipv6 pref 1 u32
filter parent 16f1: protocol ipv6 pref 1 u32 fh 800: ht divisor 1
filter parent 16f1: protocol ipv6 pref 1 u32 fh 800::800 order 2048 key ht 800 bkt 0 flowid 16f1:2
  match 00000000/ffffffff at 24
  match 00000000/ffffffff at 28
  match 00000000/ffffffff at 32
  match 00000002/ffffffff at 36
```

This PR is aimed at reducing the amount of updates required.

* py3status modules now only trigger an update if their content has actually changed.

* containers (currently only groups) can now register a function that allows py3status to be aware of the active content so updates are only triggered for content that is being displayed.  If they have not registered a function then all sub-module updates trigger an update.

This leads to a reduction in overall workload.

__example:__
```
group {
    time {}
    volume_status {}
}
```

When the group shows `time` we are updated every second. When we show `volume_status` we only update when the volume has changed etc.

